ra.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra asserts that every non-constan
t polynomial (with complex-valued coefficients) has a root (a zero, a \+
solution).  A consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra is tha
t every polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 276 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has exa
ctly " }{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 108 " roots.  An alternate formulati
on of this consequence would be that every non-constant polynomial of \+
degree " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 38 " can be factored into a produc
t of a  " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the follo
