{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 172 "Factor each polynomial and determine w
hether Maple was able to find enough linear factors to demonstrate the
 above assertion about the appropriate number of linear factors." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "
In those cases where Maple did not find enough linear factors, there i
s a reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the c
oefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rati
onal numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in fin
ding exact factors (factors where the coefficients are integers or rat
ional numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee \+
that the factors of  a polynomial will necessarily have the same kind \+
of coefficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial can be factored
.  You can force Maple to report additional (approximate) factors.  Fo
r example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#!\"\"F&,&F%F&F'F&F&,
&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 
280 18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to co
nsider additonal factors where the coefficients are allowed to include
 elements from the field extension.  It is fairly clear from the facto
riztion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that somet
hing involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there ar
e problems where there is not a obvious clue as to which specific fiel
d extension should be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropri
ate solution, then using the field extension " }{TEXT 282 4 "real" }
{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating p
oint approximation scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretendin
g I don't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h)
;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#
F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(
h,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!
\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental \+
Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }
{TEXT 283 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 
53 " real linear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 285 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some o
f the factors may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For e
xample compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
