{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about finding roots of
 polynomials (equivalently factoring polynomials into a product of lin
ear factors) asserts that if the polynomial has real coefficients -- a
ll of the polynomials we have considered (and will consider) have had \+
real coefficients -- then any complex roots (or factors) must occur in
 conjugate pairs.  For example, both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 
288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(abo
ve) all occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theorem by crea
ting three new polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 an
d 7, resp., and show that the any complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occ
ur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
